    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. that's helpful. i'm a bit worried about the \"hold harmless\" part though. does that mean there are ways the client could potentially shift their own mistakes onto me, or is it strictly about my own errors? i want to make sure i'm not being blindsided by something hidden in the wording.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The \"hold harmless\" part is definitely where the fine print gets tricky, and it makes me think of a very large, very aggressive shield that only protects the Client from *your* specific bad behavior. If the clause is written exactly as you provided, it is primarily focused on your errors—your breach of contract, your negligence, or your willful misconduct. It's designed to make sure that if your work causes a problem, you take the hit, not the Client.\n\nHowever, you are right to be worried about hidden traps, because some contracts are written with more teeth than the standard, and you need to check if they've added language that lets them shift *their* own mistakes onto you. If the clause *only* mentions things \"arising out of or occurring in connection with the Consultant's breach,\" then it's focused on your side of the fence. If it's broader, that's when the danger starts, and you might need a lawyer to look closer.",
      "source": "target",
