    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "yeah that's what i'm afraid of. it's like there's stuff buried in there that's easy to miss. what are some common ways these kinds of \"hidden\" or sneaky liabilities show up in these clauses? i'm trying to figure out if there are any specific red flag words i should be looking for to make sure im not getting screwed over.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A common way these clauses become a trap is when they use overly broad language, like a poorly-defined \"arising out of\" or \"related to.\" You want to watch out for language that doesn't clearly tie the liability back to *your* specific actions. If the clause is too vague, it can be interpreted by a judge to cover almost anything that happens while you're working, even if the Client's own poor management caused the issue. It's a big red flag if it doesn't clearly delineate the scope of your responsibility.\n\nAnother sneaky thing to look for is if the clause tries to make you indemnify them for *their* pre-existing problems or for things that are outside the scope of the work you were hired to do. If the contract says you cover losses from \"any claim,\" without specifying it relates to your performance, that's a huge warning sign. It's almost always better to have a carve-out—a specific exception—that says you are *not* responsible for their own gross negligence.",
      "source": "target",
